 self-rule =E2=80=94 growing, Tata=E2=80=99s offering was met with huge int=
erest. Investors hounded management and even showed up at the company=E2=80=
=99s headquarters to try and make their case. Within a matter of weeks, the=
 requisite capital was secured =E2=80=94 the largest raise of its kind in I=
ndia, in the industrial sector.=C2=A0
Beyond executing Jamsetji=E2=80=99s wishes, Dorabji also added to the Tata =
empire, starting a cement manufacturing division, a construction business, =
a life insurance line, as well as making forays into consumer staples like =
sugar and toiletries.=C2=A0
Not all of these extensions would last; with World War I artificially infla=
ting the demand for many of Tata=E2=80=99s industrial products. The company=
=E2=80=99s financial state reached such tenuous levels that Dorabji had to =
put up his personal capital (and his wife=E2=80=99s jewelry) to secure the =
loan that would save TISCO from dissolution. That maneuver =E2=80=94 a show=
 of impressive dedication and a willingness to take risks =E2=80=94 has bee=
n referred to as =E2=80=9Cthe finest hour of Dorabji=E2=80=99s leadership.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
JRD: Expansion and decentralization
Jehangir Ratanji Dadabhoy, better known as JRD, was a cosmopolitan man. Bor=
n in Paris to a French mother and Indian father, he was educated in the Fre=
nch capital, London, Tokyo, and Bombay. Fittingly, he boasted the elegance =
and good looks of a matinee idol, sporting a refined moustache for much of =
his life.=C2=A0
As his name suggests, JRD was a member of the Tata family, but he wasn=E2=
=80=99t a direct descendant of Jamsetji. Rather he was a cousin-once-remove=
d, chosen to step into a leadership position because of the relative dearth=
 of available grandchildren (Dorabji had no children, his brother adopted o=
ne), his notable intellect, and a strength of character that brought to min=
d Jamsetji himself. Throughout his life, JRD would prove to be someone that=
 played by the rules when it mattered =E2=80=94 he was famous for ensuring =
Tata employees never took bribes =E2=80=94 but was willing to push the boun=
daries.
In 1938, after an interregnum in which a cousin presided over the business,=
 JRD ascended to Tata Group=E2=80=99s hot seat. When he arrived, the conglo=
merate managed 14 businesses; by the time he left, there would be 95.=C2=A0
Critical additions included:=C2=A0
1939, Tata Chemicals.=C2=A0
1945, Tata Engineering and Locomotive Company (TELCO).=C2=A0
1948, Air India.=C2=A0
1949, National Radio and Engineering Company (NELCO).=C2=A0
1952, Lakm=C3=A9, a cosmetics business.=C2=A0
1954, Voltas, an air conditioning business.=C2=A0
1960, Tata Exports.=C2=A0
1963, Tata Tea, grown through the acquisition of Finlay tea.=C2=A0
1968, Tata Consulting Services (TCS), the basis for the now-dominant tech p=
ractice.
These were just the tip of the iceberg, of course. Dozens of others =E2=80=
=94 from palm oil to precision machinery =E2=80=94 peppered JRD=E2=80=99s p=
eriod of innovation.=C2=A0
Just as impressively, this growth was managed during a period of extreme po=
litical instability and change as India regained its independence and respo=
nded to the demands of different political parties.=C2=A0
For example, under Nehru, both Air India and Tata=E2=80=99s life insurance =
business were nationalized. Losing control of the former was a particular t=
ragedy for JRD who had a love for aviation that traced back to his father=
=E2=80=99s friendship with Louis Bl=C3=A9riot, the first man to fly across =
the English channel. JRD was actually the first person to receive a pilot=
=E2=80=99s license in India. (JRD also loved fast cars; he met his wife whe=
n got caught for racing his Bugatti down a Bombay boulevard and needed a la=
wyer. The lawyer=E2=80=99s daughter became his betrothed.)
But Nehru giveth as well as taketh away.=C2=A0
After banning non-essential imports, the Indian government found itself pre=
ssured by a surprising group: =E2=80=9Cthe elite women of Delhi.=E2=80=9D W=
ithout a native cosmetics supplier, women were left without make-up; to ame=
nd the problem, Nehru asked Tata to enter the space, leading to the creatio=
n of Lakm=C3=A9.=C2=A0
Indira Gandhi=E2=80=99s tenure required yet another adjustment with legisla=
tion forcing each of Tata=E2=80=99s subsidiaries to operate independently, =
governed by a board of directors. Though there were plenty of nuances to th=
e change, the upshot was profound: the parent company couldn=E2=80=99t dire=
ctly control its component pieces.=C2=A0
Thankfully, JRD didn=E2=80=99t need to rule by force. His natural magnetism=
 and the steps he had already taken to push more responsibility down to ind=
ividual companies, advancing a decentralized approach, was repaid. Even wit=
h Gandhi=E2=80=99s new rules, the conglomerate=E2=80=99s strategy was still=
 defined at the top, with individual chiefs happy to follow JRD=E2=80=99s l=
ead.=C2=A0
At the age of 87, JRD finally stepped down from his role as Chairman. He ha=
d turned Tata from a strong national player into the country=E2=80=99s defi=
ning enterprise. He turned to a younger face to take the company forward.=
=C2=A0
Ratan: Collaboration and control
Like JRD, Ratan Tata had spent some of his formative years abroad, completi=
ng high school at Riverdale Country in New York. After graduating, he compl=
eted a degree in architecture from Cornell =E2=80=94 a qualification that s=
ome suggested encapsulated Ratan=E2=80=99s well-roundedness: he was methodi=
cal, certainly, but creative, too.=C2=A0
After illustrating his business acumen in turning around NELCO, Tata=E2=80=
=99s radio division, Ratan was tapped by JRD to take his place. In 1991, he=
 officially became Tata=E2=80=99s chairman, a position he held until 2012 (=
and again as interim chair between 2016 and 2017). Tata=E2=80=99s current i=
ncarnation owes much to his vision.=C2=A0
During his tenure, Ratan focused on two critical initiatives: more tightly =
controlling the conglomerate, and positioning Tata as a global collaborator=
 and dealmaker.=C2=A0
What looks like a masterful move in one context can look limiting in anothe=
r. If JRD showed dexterity in pursuing a decentralized approach under socia=
list rule, his successor was just as wise to reverse the strategy in later =
years. Operating in an open, global economic market, Ratan concluded that T=
ata Group needed to own a greater share in its constituent companies and fo=
ster closer collaboration. Between 1992 and 2002, Ratan meaningfully increa=
sed the parent company=E2=80=99s stake in key units, growing its holding in=
 Tata Steel from 8% to 26% and expanding a 17% position in Tata Motors to 3=
2%. At the same time, Ratan instituted stronger central governance, codifyi=
ng core values, and setting up both a policy board and quality management g=
roup. This final initiative ensured best practices were distributed between=
 different units, in addition to facilitating meetings between leaders. As =
noted in The Tata Group:=C2=A0
Meetings across group companies marked the change in the Tata Group culture=
 from independent identities to a unified Tata family.
While Ratan clearly saw an open market as something of a threat, he was qui=
ck to recognize it as an opportunity, too. While Ratan sunsetted or sold un=
der-performing business lines (including Lakm=C3=A9) he also expanded Tata=
=E2=80=99s purview through partnerships.
Just as Tencent now serves as the ferryman to China (think Roblox with Luob=
ulesi [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uhDAMhU8z2RU5v5NZZNFNr4ECMRA=
VEpSYUm5fGBaVLNuSZT-_r_eEYy6HW3MldqWWjhVdwr3OSISFbRVLG4PjRlip1YsFpwK32rJY26=
EgLj7OjsqGbN26OfaeYk7vDQCh2eQsCouWaxhMD9IoriXnQRrujTEdqlvXbyFi6tHhD5YjJ2Szm=
4jW-pCfD_F1xr7vTUEfaMIRExY_x0pNn5dz1pWIQ0zj2Zbczfn3I66ZRSdAcNAgudBGQsMbEFI8=
e2E89EKBsEJJROlfFkynB-APBcsomrp1lXz_fZ1nxaVMXS7XfQXfk19wfg9Ow-1Zly1FOlpMvps=
x3CzoRvqm097vEobW0wUSQBkDAhTc3k9YUtsXf0rLTuWQz630L_oHhayMjg]), Tata has oft=
en played the same role with India, collaborating with Daimler to manufactu=
re Mercedes-Benz in the country, delivering insurance alongside behemoth AI=
G, and partnering with Starbucks to offer coffee from Kargil to Kochi. (You=
: Did they just look up the northernmost and southernmost Indian towns with=
 a hard =E2=80=9CC=E2=80=9D sound? Us, intellectuals: Tumhari himmat kaise =
hui?)
Ratan also bolstered Tata=E2=80=99s existing positions through M&A. Among h=
is key purchases:=C2=A0
2000, Tetley Group for $450 million
2004, a unit of Daewoo for $102 million
2005, NatSteel, Singapore=E2=80=99s largest steel provider, for $365 million
2006, the Ritz-Carlton in Boston for $170 million
2007, Cronus, a steelmaker, for $11.3 billion
2008, Jaguar and Land Rover for $2.3 billion
2008, General Chemical Industrial Products for $1 billion
Still, a key figure, Ratan=E2=80=99s reign served to consolidate Tata=E2=80=
=99s operations and modernize it. Immediately followed by Cyrus Mistry (mor=
e below), Ratan found a truer success in Natarajan Chandrasekaran (=E2=80=
=9CChandra=E2=80=9D). For an empire so steeped in the tenets of Zoroastrian=
ism, it was a significant appointment: Chandra was the first non-Parsi exec=
utive to take the helm.
Tata Today
=E2=80=9CYou would not probably look at the Tata Group as a modern conglome=
rate. The most important [thing] is to define themselves.=E2=80=9D
-- Anonymous source close to Tata Group, Financial Times, April 2021
Today, despite its first outside Chairman, Tata=E2=80=99s corporate structu=
re reflects its history.=C2=A0
Ordered chaos. Juxtaposition of rich and poor. Proud legacy transitioning t=
o tech-led future. Layers of new structures built on top of old.=C2=A0
It looks more like India itself than like other conglomerates.=C2=A0
Most of the world=E2=80=99s largest conglomerates are structured in a coupl=
e of ways:=C2=A0
Publicly traded parent company with wholly-owned subsidiaries or investment=
s. (Tencent, Reliance, Alibaba, Berkshire Hathaway, Constellation)
Private all the way down. (Koch)
Tata is built different.=C2=A0
First, the parent company, Tata Sons, is a Private Limited Company. It has =
just 28 shareholders, who fall into four buckets: Tata Trusts, Mistry Famil=
y (via Shapoorji Pallonji Group), Individuals (mainly Tata family members),=
 and Subsidiaries.=C2=A0
Tata is unique among multi-hundred billion dollar companies in that it is m=
ajority owned by charitable trusts. Corporate social responsibility is a bu=
zzphrase for most companies; for Tata, it=E2=80=99s structural. That struct=
ure has allowed the company to support India through COVID, with more than =
token gestures. While we noted that this week saw Tata step up its oxygen c=
ontributions, the firm has also donated $200 million to relief efforts, spe=
nt heavily on bringing supplies to India, and helped improve rapid testing =
capabilities.=C2=A0
The Tatas and their trusts are in the process of consolidating their owners=
hip even further. After a falling out related to Ratan Tata=E2=80=99s remov=
al of Cyrus Mistry as Tata Group Chairman in 2016, and a March Indian Supre=
me Court ruling [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEmOgzAQRU8T74LKA8Ysv=
OhNXwN5KIjVYCNTdJTbtxMWLZVq0NfXV73gCJdSX3YvB7F3m-i1o834PFYkwsrOA-uUouVaGNmr=
kUWrIje9YemY5oq4ubRaqiey_fRrCo5SyR8HgOjZww7BSclROY0wehi5ATVHiVxrGY0PV647Y8I=
c0OIv1lfJyFb7INqPm_y6ie9Wz-ezm6kLZWtHKJkwU9uEcCqOarhzL91dGaXufkB9dzCGWatBhd=
mzZAUIDj1ILnotoeMdCCmGILSDIBQII5RElG40oH0_A78p2BbRHac_yIWfdy6rNhfypaa8NPnn4=
TZcP0J7fWpzO3Oi14TZ-RXjRYUuuB9O04IZa4MeJ0dvpABKaxCg4KLQsMnejHyQhrXkWJor_4f-=
AS_qjDw] against Mistry=E2=80=99s claim that the ouster was illegal in Marc=
h, the two families are negotiating the Tatas=E2=80=99 purchase of the Mist=
rys=E2=80=99 18.4% stake.=C2=A0
As Tata Sons cleans up its ownership, it=E2=80=99s cleaning up the entities=
 it controls as well. In 2019, under now-Chairman Natarajan Chandra, Tata r=
eorganized its 30 listed companies and their roughly 1,000 subsidiaries int=
o ten verticals.=C2=A0
The reorganization was part of Chandra=E2=80=99s process of simplifying, sy=
nergizing, and scaling (3S). Starting under Ratan and continuing under Chan=
dra, Tata Sons is working to take advantage of its combined resources and e=
xpertise. That=E2=80=99s no small task given the ownership structure and th=
e fact that each company has its own Board of Directors.=C2=A0
It requires a light touch, sharing best practices instead of dictating. Rav=
i Arora, Tata=E2=80=99s VP of Innovation, described that loose influence on=
 the Stretch Thinking podcast:
Every company in the TATA Group impacts others in the group because we are =
one family, although every company is independent. But we do influence each=
 other, and we also learn from each other.
That=E2=80=99s hardly the top-down decision-making you=E2=80=99d expect fro=
m a company like Reliance, but it seems to be working. Tata=E2=80=99s seven=
teen public holdings combined are now worth more than Reliance, making Tata=
 India=E2=80=99s largest conglomerate.
To be sure, Reliance Industries [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMuOh=
CAQRb-m2bUpCrB1wWI28xuGR2mTVjCIY_z7odtkJuGRULk53ONMoSnlU69pK-x9DOVcSUc6tplK=
ocz2jfIQvOYtdkLJnnktPe9Ux8I2jJloMWHWJe_E1t3OwZkSUvwkAFCxp-aej4ZIIdlW4uhUJz2=
2ahS9ctxad3HN7gNFR5p-KJ8pEpv1s5R1u4mvG37XdRxHE1OxKYc4NS7Vp7XuTHMwNXifapnDnP=
c03kP0wbCgEZCDAsFRtQIa3gAKfDhsDTiUgB1KQSRM30Fr1Qj8JmGZsNl2uxXjXpWysKz_qHX8e=
pqF5s-g9h3qvewxlHOgaOxM_lJRLqMfOcNEkXL9nB9MeXsEkG0LCBKu6tWVUF3PH6JjlexTTcV_=
6C_7aYzu], helmed by Mukesh Ambani, is still cleaner. Invest in Reliance, g=
et everything that it owns. The company is complex -- it has 158 subsidiari=
es and seven associate entities across six business lines -- but it=E2=80=
=99s all wrapped up in one publicly traded stock. It=E2=80=99s the most val=
uable publicly traded Indian conglomerate with a market cap of $176 billion=
=2E And it=E2=80=99s more nimble, a poin=
t we=E2=80=99ll return to shortly.=C2=
=A0
Tata, on the other hand, isn=E2=80=99t publicly traded. Instead, it owns st=
akes in thirty-one companies, 17 of which are publicly traded, across ten v=
erticals. Many of the subsidiaries use the Tata name, which the parent comp=
any licenses to them under Brand Equity and Business Promotion agreements. =
The Tata brand alone is the most valuable in India, with an estimated value=
 of $20 billion [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkcuOwyAMRb-m7BI5PPJYs=
JjN_EZkwG1RCURAZpS_H9IuRkLG8kP36thipUfKp95TqewKaz130pF-S6BaKbOjUF6908PIZ6Hk=
wpyWbpjVzHxZ75loQx90zQex_TDBW6w-xfcGAFfsqWEanUQhR6PuFoQRoBa3iMkKoyYrx48uHs5=
TtKTph_KZIrGgn7Xu5Sa-bvy7PZMxuruP2KZ6m7ZW2jOV0mUKhIVKK1Ss2L0Hux8MB7Wc8FW6o3=
DojA-hees2zC_mNQc-gAIxcDUK6IceuOCT5SOC5RL4zKUgErjMcFmH4SZhe_C-HKZUtK_LA8s6p=
mpS9vHR2q8nbhTejQZjbf92RF_PlSKaQO7DqX5wv8mtD4qU2xncivWCDCDHEThI-HBpIIWal2ES=
M2vKLrWt-C_6B4Ablr4]. Each company operates independently under its own boa=
rd of directors.=C2=A0
As of March 31, 2020, in the early throes of the pandemic, Tata said [https=
